@*
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    BnLayoutDemo — Phase 6.1 Task 1.4 (design §"The proof surface"), route
    "/layout", mount-registry key "BnLayoutDemo".

    Phase 7.1 Gate 2: authored in .razor (mostly declarative — the form this
    page always wanted to be). Parity with the retired hand-written
    BuildRenderTree version was proven byte-for-byte by the transitional
    golden-vs-twin test (record-identical patch streams across mount + the
    Back navigation, mutation-verified) before the swap; BnLayoutDemoTests
    and both shells' frame tables hold it from here. THE FRAME TABLE BELOW
    IS UNCHANGED from the .cs original — it is the cross-platform contract
    (BnLayoutDemoTests + BnDemoFrameTables.kt/.swift via the drift test),
    and a conversion does not get to touch it.

    The flex demo is a THIRD page (6.1 design decision 2): BnDemo and
    BnSettingsPage keep their goldens on all four surfaces, so layout-engine
    bugs never arrive mixed with golden-rewrite noise.

    Its whole job is to have COMPUTED FRAMES THAT ARE FULLY PREDICTABLE,
    because three surfaces assert against them: the .NET patch golden
    (BnLayoutDemoTests), the Android instrumented frames (Gate 2) and the
    iOS XCTest frames (Gate 3) — and the last two assert THE SAME NUMBERS.
    That pairing is M6 DoD #2 ("lays out identically on both platforms"),
    so every size here is explicit and every position derives from Yoga's
    documented defaults. Yoga computes in density-independent units on both
    platforms (iOS points 1:1; Android multiplies by density at frame-apply
    time), so the table below is in dp/pt.

    ── THE FRAME TABLE (dp, each frame RELATIVE TO ITS PARENT) ──────────────

    root BnColumn                       fills the host; children stack vertically
     ├─ [0] row section   (0,   0, 300, 100)   BnRow    W=300 H=100
     │    ├─ box A        (0,   0,  50, 100)   W=50           ← cross-stretch → h=100
     │    ├─ box B        (50,  0, 200, 100)   Grow=1         ← absorbs 300-50-50
     │    └─ box C        (250, 0,  50, 100)   W=50
     ├─ [1] column sect.  (0, 100, 300, 200)   BnColumn W=300 H=200 Justify=SpaceBetween
     │    ├─ item 0       (0,   0, 100,  40)                  free = 200-3*40 = 80,
     │    ├─ item 1       (100, 80, 100,  40)   AlignSelf=Center   split into 2 gaps
     │    └─ item 2       (0, 160, 100,  40)                       of 40 → y 0/80/160
     ├─ [2] wrap section  (0, 300, 300, 100)   BnRow    W=300 H=100 Wrap=Wrap
     │    ├─ wrap 0       (0,   0,  90,  40)   line 1 (3 × 90 = 270 of 300 — 30dp
     │    ├─ wrap 1       (90,  0,  90,  40)   line 1   of slack, see below)
     │    ├─ wrap 2       (180, 0,  90,  40)   line 1
     │    └─ wrap 3       (0,  40,  90,  40)   line 2 — alignContent defaults to
     │                                          flex-start in Yoga, so line 2 sits
     │                                          at the line-1 cross size (40)
     ├─ [3] text section  (0, 400, 150,  H)    BnRow W=150, NO height
     │    └─ text leaf    (0,   0, w,    H)    w ≤ 150; H = the NATIVELY MEASURED
     │                                          height of the wrapped label
     ├─ [4] back section  (0, 400+H, 300, Hb)  BnRow W=300, NO height
     │    └─ "← Back"     (0,   0, Wb,   Hb)   Hb/Wb = the button's measured size
     └─ [5] parity section(0,  ⋯ , 300, Hp)    BnRow W=300, NO height — font
          └─ text leaf    (0,   0, wp,   Hp)   parity (#126): SINGLE-LINE, explicit
                                               FontSize=20. Hp is the SAME literal on
                                               both shells (Inter + Gate C line box) —
                                               the un-skipped `parity row` cell.

    The wrap row's boxes are 90dp, not 100. Four 100s in a 300 row would put
    three on line 1 ONLY because Yoga's break test is `consumed + item >
    available` and 300 > 300 is false — i.e. the demo would sit EXACTLY on
    the wrap boundary, and half a dp of rounding drift on either shell would
    drop box 3 to line 2 and make the two platforms "disagree" for a reason
    that has nothing to do with the engine. 90 × 3 = 270 leaves 30dp of
    slack: the break is unambiguous.

    Rows [3] and [4] are the DoD #3 proof and carry no fixed height —
    deliberately: a MULTI-LINE label at each shell's platform-default size, and
    a native button, are not constants we get to invent. The shells assert them
    RELATIONALLY (H > 0; the text row's height EQUALS the leaf's measured
    height; the back row starts at y = 400 + H). Row [5] is the font-parity
    proof (#126): a SINGLE-LINE leaf at an EXPLICIT shared FontSize, whose
    height IS a cross-shell literal (Hp) once CI measures it — the un-skipped
    `parity row` cell. Everything above these measured rows is a fixed number
    on both platforms, which is why they all sit at the END of the column: a
    font-dependent height must not shift the frames the parity assertion is
    built on.

    Nav parity with the other pages: "← Back" → INavigationManager → "/".
    Reachable by mount-name ("BnLayoutDemo") and by route ("/layout"); no
    button on BnDemo points here — adding one would churn BnDemo's four
    goldens for no engine reason (non-negotiable #4).

    A fresh ROOT component (like BnSettingsPage): no cascaded theme crosses
    a root swap.
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*@
<BnColumn>
    @* [0] fixed 50 · Grow=1 · fixed 50, inside a 300×100 row. The grow box
       absorbs exactly the remainder (200); the boxes have no height, so the
       row's default cross-axis stretch gives them its full 100. *@
    <BnRow Width="300" Height="100">
        <BnView Width="50" BackgroundColor="@BoxA" />
        <BnView Grow="1" BackgroundColor="@BoxB" />
        <BnView Width="50" BackgroundColor="@BoxC" />
    </BnRow>

    @* [1] space-between over a 200-high column: three 40-high items → 80dp
       of free space split into two 40dp gaps (y = 0 / 80 / 160). The middle
       item overrides the cross axis with AlignSelf=Center → x = (300-100)/2. *@
    <BnColumn Width="300" Height="200" Justify="FlexJustify.SpaceBetween">
        <BnView Width="100" Height="40" BackgroundColor="@Item0" />
        <BnView Width="100" Height="40" AlignSelf="FlexAlign.Center" BackgroundColor="@Item1" />
        <BnView Width="100" Height="40" BackgroundColor="@Item2" />
    </BnColumn>

    @* [2] four 90-wide boxes in a 300-wide wrapping row: three fit on line 1
       (270 of 300), the fourth overflows onto line 2 at y = 40 (the line-1
       cross size — Yoga's alignContent defaults to flex-start).
       90, not 100, ON PURPOSE: four 100s would leave the row sitting exactly
       on Yoga's break boundary (consumed + item > available; 300 > 300 is
       false), where a half-dp of rounding on either shell flips box 3 onto
       line 2. 30dp of slack makes the break a fact, not a coin toss. *@
    <BnRow Width="300" Height="100" Wrap="FlexWrap.Wrap">
        @for (var i = 0; i < 4; i++)
        {
            <BnView Width="90" Height="40" BackgroundColor="@WrapBox" />
        }
    </BnRow>

    @* [3] the DoD #3 proof: a 150-wide row with NO height. The label cannot
       fit on one line, so the shell's Yoga measure function reports its
       WRAPPED height — and the row hugs it. Nothing above this section
       depends on that height (it is the second-to-last child), so the fixed
       frames stay fixed on both platforms. *@
    <BnRow Width="150">
        <BnText Text="@MeasuredText" />
    </BnRow>

    @* [4] nav parity with BnDemo/BnSettingsPage — and a second measured leaf
       (a button sizes itself). *@
    <BnRow Width="300">
        <BnButton Label="← Back" OnClick="GoBack" />
    </BnRow>

    @* [5] the font-parity proof (#126). Unlike [3]'s MULTI-LINE label at each
       shell's platform-default size, this is a SINGLE-LINE leaf at an EXPLICIT
       shared FontSize (20). With the bundled Inter and Android's normalized line
       box (includeFontPadding=false, Gate C), one line of Inter at 20 measures to
       the SAME height on both shells — so its row's measured height is a CROSS-
       SHELL LITERAL, the frame-table `parity row` cell the drift test now pins by
       number instead of by MEASURED token. It sits LAST so its font-dependent
       height shifts nothing above it. Text is short enough never to wrap at 300. *@
    <BnRow Width="300">
        <BnText Text="Parity 20pt" FontSize="20" />
    </BnRow>
</BnColumn>

@code {
    // Distinct per-box colours: the AVD/simulator screenshots are read by
    // humans too, and a wrong frame is easier to SEE than to diff.
    private const string BoxA = "#E57373"; // red
    private const string BoxB = "#64B5F6"; // blue  — the Grow=1 box
    private const string BoxC = "#81C784"; // green
    private const string Item0 = "#FFB74D"; // orange
    private const string Item1 = "#BA68C8"; // purple — the AlignSelf=Center child
    private const string Item2 = "#4DB6AC"; // teal
    private const string WrapBox = "#90A4AE"; // grey

    /// <summary>The long label whose NATIVELY MEASURED size drives its frame
    /// (DoD #3): 150dp of row is far too narrow for it, so it must wrap and
    /// report a multi-line height — and its row must grow to that height.</summary>
    private const string MeasuredText =
        "This label is measured natively: it wraps inside 150dp and its measured height drives the row.";

    [Inject] public INavigationManager Navigation { get; set; } = default!;

    private Task GoBack() => Navigation.NavigateToAsync("/").AsTask();
}
